Note:
This file implements RAW PAGE ALLOCATION for the Runa runtime memory system.

PAGE ALLOCATION - Direct mmap/munmap Page Allocator
- Process raw anonymous-page allocation via the platform mmap syscall
- Process raw page deallocation via the platform munmap syscall
- Process page-allocator-based reallocation (allocate-copy-free composition)

This file is essential because of the following reasons:
- Raw page allocation is the substrate that the higher tiers (arena,
  chained arena, owned heap) build on. They use it to acquire large
  multi-page buffers without paying the malloc/free overhead.
- A page-granular allocator must exist somewhere in the runtime; this is
  the canonical home for the raw mmap/munmap wrappers callers will use
  when they want to manage their own pages rather than go through the
  owned-heap registry.
- Centralising the prot/flag composition in one place prevents callers
  from hardcoding x86_64-Linux-specific magic numbers (PROT_READ=1,
  MAP_PRIVATE=2 etc.) - the Syscall module supplies the platform-correct
  values, and this module composes them once.

This file consists of the following functions/features/operation types:
- page_allocate (size) - allocate anonymous private pages
- page_free (ptr, size) - munmap the pages
- page_reallocate (ptr, old, new) - resize via allocate-copy-free

Migration history:
- 2026-05-18: Moved from compiler/internal/memory_utils.runa into the runtime
  tree per the CEO-ratified "memory management lives in runtime/core/memory/"
  ruling. The pre-migration source defined local PROT_READ/PROT_WRITE and
  MAP_PRIVATE/MAP_ANONYMOUS constants that hardcoded x86_64-Linux magic
  numbers (1, 2, 2, 32). The move replaces those locals with calls to the
  Syscall module's platform-aware accessors, fixing a latent
  cross-platform-correctness defect where the constants would be silently
  wrong on every non-Linux-x86_64 target. The Processes are also renamed
  from syscall_malloc/syscall_free/syscall_realloc to page_allocate/
  page_free/page_reallocate so the names describe what the functions do
  (page allocation) rather than what they imitate (malloc).

Dependencies:
- Imports compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/syscall.runa for the
  platform-correct mmap/munmap entrypoints and the PROT_* / MAP_* value
  accessors.
- Imports compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa for the
  memory_copy primitive used by page_reallocate.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/syscall.runa" as Syscall
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as MemoryCore

Note:
============================================================================
Page Allocator Constants
============================================================================
:End Note

Note:
ANON_FD is the file descriptor passed to mmap for anonymous mappings. POSIX
mmap requires this to be -1 on platforms that observe the fd argument for
MAP_ANONYMOUS, and ignores it on the others. -1 is the portable choice.
:End Note

Constant ANON_FD as Integer is -1

Constant ANON_OFFSET as Integer is 0

Note:
============================================================================
Raw Page Allocation
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "page_allocate" takes size as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Allocate a contiguous region of anonymous private pages via mmap.
        Returns the base address of the mapping on success, 0 on failure.
        The caller chooses the size; the kernel rounds it up to the next
        page boundary internally and the caller is responsible for
        remembering the size they requested (because munmap needs it).
        This is the lowest-level allocator the runtime exposes; everything
        else (arena, chained arena, owned heap) is implemented on top of it.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. Read the platform-correct PROT_READ and PROT_WRITE flags
               from the Syscall module and combine them with OR (encoded
               as addition because the bit patterns are disjoint on every
               supported platform).
            2. Read the platform-correct MAP_PRIVATE and MAP_ANONYMOUS
               flags and combine them the same way.
            3. Call syscall_mmap with addr=0 (kernel picks the address),
               length=size, the composed prot and flags, fd=-1, offset=0.
            4. mmap returns the mapped address on success or a negative
               error code on failure. Translate negative -> 0 so callers
               see the simple "zero means failure" convention used
               throughout the runtime.

        Migration note (2026-05-18): the pre-migration source hardcoded
            Let prot_flags be PROT_READ plus PROT_WRITE  Note: 1 + 2 = 3
            Let map_flags be MAP_PRIVATE plus MAP_ANONYMOUS  Note: 2 + 32 = 34
        with the right-hand-side comments revealing that the local
        constants were x86_64-Linux-specific. The values are different on
        macOS (MAP_ANONYMOUS=0x1000=4096) and other platforms. The new
        body queries Syscall for the correct platform values at runtime.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        One mmap syscall - hundreds of cycles minimum (kernel transition,
        VMA setup, possible TLB invalidation). Not suitable for small
        allocations; use TIER 2 arena or TIER 3 owned-heap for those.
        Suitable for allocations >= one page (4KB on most platforms).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Anonymous mmap mappings are zero-filled by the kernel on first
        access, so this function never returns memory containing another
        process's data. The MAP_PRIVATE flag ensures writes do not leak
        to a backing file. The PROT_READ | PROT_WRITE choice means the
        returned pages are NOT executable - callers wanting executable
        pages must call mmap directly with PROT_EXEC; we deliberately do
        not expose an "executable page" entrypoint here because the
        W^X discipline says read/write and execute should be requested
        explicitly, not by default.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let prot_flags be proc PROT_READ from Syscall plus proc PROT_WRITE from Syscall
    Let map_flags be proc MAP_PRIVATE from Syscall plus proc MAP_ANONYMOUS from Syscall

    Let ptr be proc syscall_mmap from Syscall with 0, size, prot_flags, map_flags, ANON_FD, ANON_OFFSET

    Note: mmap returns a negative error code on failure
    If ptr is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return ptr
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
Raw Page Deallocation
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "page_free" takes ptr as Integer, size as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Unmap a region previously mapped by page_allocate. mmap on every
        supported platform requires the caller to remember the original
        size and pass it to munmap; the kernel has no way to look up the
        size from the address alone (it only knows the VMA, which may
        cover more than one original mapping after merging). Hence the
        size parameter is mandatory and must match what was passed to
        page_allocate.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL guard: ptr == 0 -> reject (return 0). munmap on a
               null pointer is implementation-defined on some kernels
               and we want a deterministic refusal.
            2. Size guard: size <= 0 -> reject. munmap with a zero or
               negative length is invalid and the kernel will return
               EINVAL; we catch it earlier so the failure mode is
               consistent.
            3. Call syscall_munmap(ptr, size). Negative result means the
               syscall failed (EINVAL most commonly: the address range
               does not correspond to a live mapping).
            4. Return 1 on success, 0 on failure.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        One munmap syscall plus a TLB shootdown for any pages that were
        actually touched. For very large mappings, the TLB shootdown
        dominates and can take milliseconds on busy systems.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        munmap on the wrong address range can free a different mapping
        than the caller intended, exposing the slot to immediate reuse
        by a subsequent allocation. The size argument is the principal
        defence against this - passing the correct size ensures the
        kernel only unmaps the originally allocated extent. Callers
        must therefore record sizes alongside pointers when they call
        page_allocate.
    @End Security_Scope

    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If size is less than or equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let result be proc syscall_munmap from Syscall with ptr, size

    If result is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
Raw Page Reallocation
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "page_reallocate" takes ptr as Integer, old_size as Integer, new_size as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Resize a previously page-allocated buffer. The implementation is
        the allocate-copy-free composition because mmap does not provide
        an in-place resize entrypoint on every supported platform (Linux
        has mremap, Darwin does not). The behaviour is deliberately
        symmetric with the C realloc convention: ptr == 0 means
        "allocate fresh", new_size == 0 means "free the buffer".
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. ptr == 0: caller has no existing buffer, delegate to
               page_allocate(new_size) and return its result.
            2. new_size == 0: caller wants to free the buffer, delegate
               to page_free(ptr, old_size) and return 0 (the "freed"
               canonical zero pointer).
            3. Allocate the new buffer with page_allocate(new_size).
               On failure return 0; the old buffer is left intact (this
               matches the realloc convention - failure does NOT
               invalidate the original pointer).
            4. Choose copy_size = min(old_size, new_size). On shrink,
               we copy only new_size bytes; on grow, we copy all of
               old_size and the remainder of new_buffer is zero-filled
               by mmap.
            5. memory_copy(new_ptr, ptr, copy_size).
            6. page_free(ptr, old_size) to release the original.
            7. Return new_ptr.

        Migration note (2026-05-18): the pre-migration source called
            Return proc syscall_malloc from Syscall with new_size
        which was wrong - syscall_malloc is the same-file Process being
        defined, not a Syscall member. The qualified form resolved only
        because of import flattening in stage-1; the canonical form is
        the same-file self-call (`proc page_allocate with new_size`) and
        the migration rewrites it that way.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        Two mmap syscalls plus one memory_copy plus one munmap. For
        very large resizes, the memory_copy dominates; on Linux a future
        optimisation could call mremap directly when the caller can
        tolerate address changes (MREMAP_MAYMOVE) - but mremap is not
        portable, so the portable composition lives here.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        On shrink, the bytes between new_size and old_size are discarded
        by the munmap and the kernel reclaims their physical backing.
        Callers who want to ensure sensitive data is wiped before unmap
        must memory_zero the tail before calling page_reallocate; the
        function itself does not zero on shrink to avoid imposing the
        cost on callers that do not need it.
    @End Security_Scope

    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Note: No existing buffer - delegate to a fresh allocation
        Return proc page_allocate with new_size
    End If

    If new_size is equal to 0:
        Note: Resize to zero is equivalent to free
        Let dummy be proc page_free with ptr, old_size
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Allocate the new region
    Let new_ptr be proc page_allocate with new_size

    If new_ptr is equal to 0:
        Note: Allocation failed - leave original buffer intact per realloc convention
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Copy the minimum of old_size and new_size bytes
    Let copy_size be old_size
    If new_size is less than old_size:
        Set copy_size to new_size
    End If

    Let dummy be proc memory_copy from MemoryCore with new_ptr, ptr, copy_size

    Note: Free the old region
    Set dummy to proc page_free with ptr, old_size

    Return new_ptr
End Process
